^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's count Bonnie's points. She has 19 HCP, has 2 length points, and has 1 quality suit point for 22 points. She should subtracts 2 for the 2 Qx suits—dubious doubletons, getting back down to 20 Starting Points. With 20 points, she has a game forcing hand. 3S is not game forcing. I can, and often do pass that bid. |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also, her spade suit is "self sufficient." That means that it passes the "singleton test." If a suit is a reasonable trump suit when partner has a singleton, then it is self sufficient. So Bonnie has a clear 4S bid. |
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Usually responder is "captain", meaning responder is responsible for placing thee final contract. But when you open with a maximum hand (18+) and responder shows 6 or more then opener becomes captain, and must ensure the partnership gets to game. |
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In such circumstances opener must make a forcing bid or bid game. Jumping to 3 is not a forcing bid, it only shows a medium hand. |
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Opener has 2 rebids available that are forcing—jump shifts and reverses. A jump shift (e.g. 1C-P-1H-P-2S) shows a max (18+) opener and establishes a game force; the partnership may not stop below game.  A reverse (e.g. 1C-P-1S-P-2H) shows a medium or max hand (16+) and is a one round force, not a game force; if opener reverses with a max hand, opener is still responsible for getting their side to game.|
