UP|44|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First the opening lead. A heart was good. But against suits, you lead the top of a 2 card honor sequence. So since  the @HJ10 is an honor sequence, the @HJ is the correct lead. I see many less experienced players lead 4th best against suits, when they have an honor sequence. As I will explain, leading a low heart gave Bonnie the potential for making the hand.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In NT there is a slight difference. There you need to lead top only when you have a 3-card honor sequence. The reason for leading top in suits is, against suits, often suits only last 2 rounds before being trumped. So you want to take fast tricks. But in NT, suits are not trumped, so  you can afford to  go slower.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|4s was a reasonable contract. the heart lead is the only thing that gives Bonnie trouble, as it prematurely removes dummy's entry. So after the heart lead, the hand can be made, but it is very tricky. Bonnie is worried about losing 2 diamonds, 1 club, and 1 heart. But she does not have 2 diamond losers right away, since dummy has a singleton, and a trump.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The way Bonnie played the hand, she will always go down 1, losing 2 diamonds, 1 heart, and 1 club (unless the CK is singleton). On the other hand. The way the first 2 tricks were played (2 rounds of hearts), she has a chance to make it. So long as there is a trump on dummy, she only has 1 immediate diamond loser. However, as soon as she draws any trump, dummy is out so she then has 2 diamond losers.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Her best shot is to try and set up a trick in dummy for a discard. And her best shot is to immediately knock out the @CK by playing a low club at trick 3. On the actual hand, if East wins the CK and plays another club, West will ruff, and Bonnie will go down. |
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But:
a) On some hands, clubs will be 2-2.
b) On this hand, East may duck the club and Bonnie can then pitch a diamond on a heart.
c) East may win the CK and play a card other than another club, not figuring out that partner is out of clubs. |
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|An expert would figure that out, but an expert would also have led a trump rather than a heart at trick 2. The point is, it is easy to make a defensive error on this hand. Even a pretty good East might decide to lead a trump after winning the CK. And if East does anything but lead a club, Bonnie will make the hand.|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This hand illustrates an important point about when not to draw trump immediately. And that is, when you need trumps in dummy to limit your losers in a suit (diamonds on this hand), you need to avoid drawing trumps and set up your other winners first. |
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I suspect if you review my declarer play lesson on drawing trumps, there will be a hand that illustrates this point. BTW, it just so happens that Marty's next voice lesson is on drawing trumps. Nevertheless,
This is a very hard hand to play. |
